1
00:00:37,900 --> 00:00:39,270
What's going on?

2
00:00:39,270 --> 00:00:40,900
I don't think he's feeling well.

3
00:00:48,350 --> 00:00:49,330
Dr. Cha.

4
00:00:49,330 --> 00:00:50,610
Are you all right?

5
00:01:13,900 --> 00:01:15,260
Dr. Cha.

6
00:01:22,470 --> 00:01:24,320
I'm right here.

7
00:01:28,850 --> 00:01:30,180
Look at me.

8
00:01:32,970 --> 00:01:34,760
Yes, you're seeing me.

9
00:01:50,930 --> 00:01:52,860
I'll do it.

10
00:01:52,860 --> 00:01:55,190
Please trust me.

11
00:02:05,610 --> 00:02:07,480
This was unexpected...

12
00:02:08,380 --> 00:02:09,810
My apologies.

13
00:02:11,660 --> 00:02:14,180
As I said earlier, she is the

14
00:02:14,180 --> 00:02:16,860
second-year resident on our team.

15
00:02:16,860 --> 00:02:18,190
She is...

16
00:02:19,220 --> 00:02:20,860
more ambitious than she looks.

17
00:02:20,860 --> 00:02:24,480
Since she gave me
a crucial hint, I think...

18
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:27,500
she wants to explain it herself.

19
00:02:29,200 --> 00:02:30,550
Let's hear it.

20
00:03:10,590 --> 00:03:12,780
A second-year resident at

21
00:03:12,780 --> 00:03:15,500
Seoul Hansae Hospital's Department of
Anesthesiology and Pain Medicine.

22
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:16,990
I'm Kang Shi Young.

23
00:03:16,990 --> 00:03:20,000
The reason I can speak about this is

24
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:24,180
due to receiving a hint from another
patient I was in charge of.

25
00:03:29,810 --> 00:03:31,210
That patient...

26
00:03:31,210 --> 00:03:33,880
was experiencing stabbing,
burning pains

27
00:03:33,880 --> 00:03:38,280
in the area between his chest,
shoulders, and arms.

28
00:03:38,280 --> 00:03:41,790
The patient was diagnosed with
zoster sine herpete in the end.

29
00:03:41,790 --> 00:03:43,490
I'll help you.

30
00:03:43,490 --> 00:03:46,950
You're endlessly monitoring
your body which won't talk

31
00:03:46,950 --> 00:03:49,670
and must hide that fact as well.

32
00:03:49,670 --> 00:03:51,500
So I'll help you.

33
00:03:51,500 --> 00:03:53,390
I'll do whatever I can.

34
00:03:55,890 --> 00:03:58,940
During that process, I got the hint.

35
00:03:58,940 --> 00:04:02,450
As Dr. Cha mentioned just now,

36
00:04:02,450 --> 00:04:05,060
"He felt pain because
there wasn't any."

37
00:04:05,060 --> 00:04:07,410
It's related to this phrase.

38
00:04:08,200 --> 00:04:09,680
[ Zinmu Rijund ]

39
00:04:12,280 --> 00:04:14,460
Can I help you?

40
00:04:15,310 --> 00:04:17,110
[ Han Min Joo: Zinmu Rijund Sales Team ]

41
00:04:17,110 --> 00:04:19,620
"A Conversation About Death."

42
00:04:19,620 --> 00:04:22,220
- Pardon?
- I'm a member of that group.

43
00:04:26,660 --> 00:04:28,220
Oh, this right here.

44
00:04:29,460 --> 00:04:32,060
It looked familiar. I think I saw it there.

45
00:04:32,900 --> 00:04:34,200
That's right.

46
00:04:34,200 --> 00:04:37,400
Zinmu Rijund runs Moonlight
Foundation, which caters to

47
00:04:37,400 --> 00:04:41,100
patients with rare, incurable diseases,
and terminal cases.

48
00:04:41,980 --> 00:04:44,180
[ Moonlight Foundation ]

49
00:04:44,180 --> 00:04:48,590
He was confirmed to be suffering
from "central sensitization."

50
00:04:48,590 --> 00:04:50,170
[ Thank you for your attention ]

51
00:04:50,170 --> 00:04:53,120
My humble explanation stops right here.

52
00:04:53,120 --> 00:04:55,140
Thank you for listening.

53
00:04:56,460 --> 00:04:58,130
And finally...

54
00:04:58,130 --> 00:05:03,170
even though we're introducing the
CIPA patient as rare and incurable,

55
00:05:03,170 --> 00:05:04,610
truthfully...

56
00:05:06,220 --> 00:05:07,950
I don't believe this disease

57
00:05:07,950 --> 00:05:10,580
to be special or unique.

58
00:05:10,580 --> 00:05:12,230
The reason being

59
00:05:12,230 --> 00:05:15,050
that most patients at the
Dept. of Pain Medicine

60
00:05:15,050 --> 00:05:18,060
are experiencing invisible pains.

61
00:05:18,060 --> 00:05:22,060
Dr. Cha taught us the best way
to catch these culprits

62
00:05:22,060 --> 00:05:24,620
inside our patients.

63
00:05:25,770 --> 00:05:27,620
"Don't look at the symptoms,

64
00:05:27,620 --> 00:05:30,390
but look at the person
experiencing them."

65
00:05:30,390 --> 00:05:33,020
"Doctors are dealing with...

66
00:05:33,020 --> 00:05:35,590
the people, not the diseases."

67
00:05:37,500 --> 00:05:38,880
That's all.

68
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:40,180
Thank you.

69
00:05:57,900 --> 00:06:00,730
Our manager will give you the details.

70
00:06:00,730 --> 00:06:01,880
Please wait a moment.

71
00:06:01,880 --> 00:06:04,180
Give the brochures to all the doctors.

72
00:06:04,180 --> 00:06:05,430
- Hurry and line up.
- Yes, sir.

73
00:06:05,430 --> 00:06:06,780
- Department Manager.
- Yes.

74
00:06:06,780 --> 00:06:08,520
This gentleman here...

75
00:06:11,010 --> 00:06:13,500
Thank you. This way, please.

76
00:06:13,500 --> 00:06:15,250
Thank you, thank you.

77
00:06:18,670 --> 00:06:21,180
Wow, Kang Shi Young, daebak.

78
00:06:21,180 --> 00:06:24,160
Did you and Dr. Cha agree
to have you take over?

79
00:06:26,860 --> 00:06:28,640
Good job, Shi Young.

80
00:06:28,640 --> 00:06:29,680
Auntie.

81
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:31,440
You were so darn sharp.

82
00:06:31,440 --> 00:06:33,040
I was so surprised.

83
00:06:33,040 --> 00:06:34,490
But Dr. Cha...

84
00:06:34,490 --> 00:06:36,300
Is he ill?

85
00:06:36,300 --> 00:06:39,320
It was probably a dizzy spell.

86
00:06:39,320 --> 00:06:41,120
He seems fine now.

87
00:06:41,120 --> 00:06:43,210
I'll introduce you later.

88
00:06:43,210 --> 00:06:44,960
Thank you.

89
00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:47,630
Is it stage fright or what?

90
00:06:50,880 --> 00:06:53,590
He's always so critical.

91
00:06:53,590 --> 00:06:55,570
Good job, everyone.

92
00:06:55,570 --> 00:06:57,750
- Have a good day.
- Goodbye.

93
00:06:59,190 --> 00:07:00,640
But Dr. Cha...

94
00:07:00,640 --> 00:07:03,280
Is he not feeling well?

95
00:07:03,280 --> 00:07:06,490
He seemed a bit off earlier.
And pale, too.

96
00:07:06,490 --> 00:07:07,460
Okay.

97
00:07:07,460 --> 00:07:09,270
Let's all go outside.

98
00:07:09,270 --> 00:07:11,590
I'll escort Dr. Cha out
after we wrap up.

99
00:07:11,590 --> 00:07:13,190
- Yes, sir.
- Okay.

100
00:07:20,240 --> 00:07:21,440
Kang Shi Young.

101
00:07:23,320 --> 00:07:24,630
Give us a minute.

102
00:07:34,270 --> 00:07:36,840
The professors are curious about you.

103
00:07:36,840 --> 00:07:37,870
Say hello.

104
00:07:39,120 --> 00:07:40,690
Hello, I'm...

105
00:07:40,690 --> 00:07:43,260
We heard your introduction,
no need to repeat.

106
00:07:43,260 --> 00:07:45,850
You're such a competent resident.

107
00:07:45,850 --> 00:07:47,780
We wanted to meet you in person.

108
00:07:48,980 --> 00:07:51,190
Thank you for your kind words.

109
00:07:51,190 --> 00:07:53,110
We'll see you at the next conference.

110
00:07:53,110 --> 00:07:54,370
See you next time.

111
00:07:54,370 --> 00:07:56,600
- See you soon.
- Yes, thank you.

112
00:07:58,280 --> 00:07:59,950
See you next time.

113
00:07:59,950 --> 00:08:01,740
Thank you.

114
00:08:28,240 --> 00:08:30,010
- Great job, Doctor!
- Geez, you startled me.

115
00:08:30,970 --> 00:08:32,530
My apologies.

116
00:08:32,530 --> 00:08:34,980
I'm the sales manager of
Zinmu Rijund, Jeong Chan Suk.

117
00:08:34,980 --> 00:08:36,780
Oh, I see.

118
00:08:36,780 --> 00:08:38,270
Doctor.

119
00:08:40,210 --> 00:08:42,400
Well then, we'll see you later.

120
00:08:45,280 --> 00:08:46,830
He threw me off.

121
00:08:48,140 --> 00:08:50,190
Where are Dr. Cha and Kang Shi Young?

122
00:08:50,190 --> 00:08:51,960
They told us to go ahead.

123
00:08:51,960 --> 00:08:53,640
- Let's go.
- Okay.

124
00:08:53,640 --> 00:08:55,070
After you.

125
00:09:06,910 --> 00:09:08,710
I should listen to you.

126
00:09:08,710 --> 00:09:10,470
I should go to the hospital.

127
00:09:10,470 --> 00:09:12,640
You had ringing in your
ears earlier, right?

128
00:09:13,580 --> 00:09:14,420
Yes.

129
00:09:15,360 --> 00:09:16,940
What about now?

130
00:09:16,940 --> 00:09:18,640
How about a fever?

131
00:09:25,650 --> 00:09:27,210
I wouldn't know.

132
00:09:28,530 --> 00:09:30,930
Even if I touch it, I won't know.

133
00:09:30,930 --> 00:09:33,660
Whether it's hot or cold.

134
00:10:00,380 --> 00:10:03,040
No fever, thank God.

135
00:10:03,040 --> 00:10:06,600
- But please go the hospital...
- When I saw you earlier...

136
00:10:06,600 --> 00:10:11,450
I wasn't sure if you were
really there or not.

137
00:10:11,450 --> 00:10:14,060
"I'm right here."

138
00:10:14,060 --> 00:10:16,790
That's what I thought
you were saying,

139
00:10:16,790 --> 00:10:18,830
yet I wasn't certain.

140
00:10:22,450 --> 00:10:24,140
But I just believed.

141
00:10:26,260 --> 00:10:28,620
I believed you would
be standing there.

142
00:10:30,260 --> 00:10:31,850
Because...

143
00:10:31,850 --> 00:10:34,890
you would say that to me.

144
00:10:37,780 --> 00:10:39,350
I'll admit it.

145
00:10:40,240 --> 00:10:42,380
I do need your help.

146
00:10:45,450 --> 00:10:47,030
Thank you in advance.

147
00:10:53,320 --> 00:10:55,020
Any time.

148
00:11:03,970 --> 00:11:06,480
I think I'll wrap up here.

149
00:11:06,480 --> 00:11:08,520
Will you go to the hospital?

150
00:11:08,600 --> 00:11:09,600
Yeah.

151
00:11:11,260 --> 00:11:12,520
Yes, I will.

152
00:11:17,360 --> 00:11:18,630
Dr. Cha!

153
00:11:21,010 --> 00:11:22,760
Everything will be okay.

154
00:11:24,440 --> 00:11:26,800
Please call me after
your hospital visit.

155
00:12:13,100 --> 00:12:14,700
[ 2019 Anesthesiology and
Pain Medicine Conference ]

156
00:12:31,710 --> 00:12:34,600
[ Gyeongseo University Hospital ]

157
00:12:34,600 --> 00:12:36,600
[ Hearing Examination Room ]

158
00:13:26,480 --> 00:13:27,680
How is it?

159
00:13:28,770 --> 00:13:31,360
I want to run a few more tests.

160
00:13:31,360 --> 00:13:32,970
An MRI, a brain CT,

161
00:13:32,970 --> 00:13:34,690
a cerebrovascular CT, etc.

162
00:13:35,700 --> 00:13:38,920
You understand what I mean, right?

163
00:13:41,030 --> 00:13:43,290
Let's do everything we can for now.

164
00:13:44,900 --> 00:13:46,510
How much time...

165
00:13:46,510 --> 00:13:51,030
do I have left as a doctor?

166
00:14:03,230 --> 00:14:05,960
[ Doctor John ]
[ Episode 10: An impending doom
on a sunny afternoon ]

167
00:15:02,160 --> 00:15:03,940
Once every 30 seconds, huh?

168
00:15:03,940 --> 00:15:06,060
Just what are you checking on?

169
00:15:07,430 --> 00:15:08,630
Good job, everyone.

170
00:15:08,630 --> 00:15:10,310
Dr. Cha went home first.

171
00:15:10,310 --> 00:15:12,040
Is something the matter?

172
00:15:12,040 --> 00:15:14,350
Well, I don't know the details.

173
00:15:14,350 --> 00:15:16,970
I only heard it's a personal matter.

174
00:15:16,970 --> 00:15:18,270
All right.

175
00:15:18,270 --> 00:15:20,750
Let's call it a day and go out...

176
00:15:20,750 --> 00:15:22,380
for drinks? Cool?

177
00:15:22,380 --> 00:15:23,860
Okay, cool, cool.

178
00:15:24,980 --> 00:15:26,640
Gotcha!

179
00:15:26,640 --> 00:15:27,750
You're seeing someone, huh?

180
00:15:27,750 --> 00:15:29,190
Who is it, who is it, who is it?

181
00:15:29,200 --> 00:15:31,300
I'll get going first.
See you all tomorrow.

182
00:15:33,680 --> 00:15:35,310
She really is seeing someone.

183
00:15:35,310 --> 00:15:36,500
- Right, right?
- Yeah.

184
00:15:36,500 --> 00:15:37,570
I'll follow her.

185
00:15:37,570 --> 00:15:39,170
Dr. Heo.

186
00:15:39,170 --> 00:15:41,830
Okay, let's all go out for some beer.

187
00:15:41,830 --> 00:15:42,790
Let's go!

188
00:15:42,790 --> 00:15:45,070
- Go, go, go!
- Let's go.

189
00:15:48,200 --> 00:15:49,500
[ 2019 Anesthesiology and
Pain Medicine Conference ]

190
00:15:50,260 --> 00:15:51,600
Let's eat.

191
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:52,910
I'm hungry.

192
00:15:55,390 --> 00:15:58,010
Dr. Cha, I'm outside.

193
00:15:58,010 --> 00:15:59,550
Where should I meet you?

194
00:16:14,850 --> 00:16:16,200
It's freaking delish.

195
00:16:17,170 --> 00:16:19,780
Dr. Lee, how long will you
stay at our hospital?

196
00:16:19,780 --> 00:16:20,990
Well...

197
00:16:20,990 --> 00:16:22,980
I'll hang on until I'm
an assistant professor.

198
00:16:22,980 --> 00:16:24,250
Assistant professor?

199
00:16:24,250 --> 00:16:26,790
Dr. Lee, you were the academic type?

200
00:16:26,790 --> 00:16:28,140
You don't seem like one.

201
00:16:28,140 --> 00:16:29,280
How do I look then?

202
00:16:29,280 --> 00:16:30,840
Well, the one...

203
00:16:30,840 --> 00:16:33,300
who opens up a clinic
and rakes in money?

204
00:16:34,670 --> 00:16:36,480
People live longer these days.

205
00:16:36,480 --> 00:16:37,810
If you open up a clinic,

206
00:16:37,810 --> 00:16:41,460
all the elderly will be lining up...

207
00:16:41,460 --> 00:16:43,270
Please hook me up when you do.

208
00:16:43,270 --> 00:16:46,050
But Dr. Heo, aren't you going
into anesthesiology?

209
00:16:46,050 --> 00:16:47,270
I know.

210
00:16:47,270 --> 00:16:49,240
He says patients in pain depress him.

211
00:16:49,240 --> 00:16:50,800
Well...

212
00:16:50,800 --> 00:16:54,390
after Dr. Cha joined us, Pain Medicine
has become more dynamic.

213
00:16:54,390 --> 00:16:56,370
It's fun learning from
him and rewarding.

214
00:16:56,370 --> 00:16:58,640
There's some of that, too.

215
00:16:58,640 --> 00:17:00,290
It's fun and rewarding?

216
00:17:00,290 --> 00:17:01,650
Wow, that's great.

217
00:17:01,650 --> 00:17:03,430
Geez, whatever.

218
00:17:03,430 --> 00:17:05,490
What are you staring at?

219
00:17:05,490 --> 00:17:06,520
Are you seeing someone?

220
00:17:06,520 --> 00:17:08,350
Dating is off-limits here.

221
00:17:08,350 --> 00:17:09,610
Especially between colleagues.

222
00:17:09,610 --> 00:17:11,670
Who'd date among our department?

223
00:17:11,670 --> 00:17:13,220
That's not it.

224
00:17:13,220 --> 00:17:14,740
Take a look at this.

225
00:17:17,400 --> 00:17:20,960
In the Netherlands, there is the
Ambulance Wish Foundation.

226
00:17:20,960 --> 00:17:23,010
They grant terminal
patients' dying wishes.

227
00:17:23,010 --> 00:17:24,500
I saw this clip, too.

228
00:17:24,500 --> 00:17:28,990
This terminal patient applied
because he had a wish.

229
00:17:28,990 --> 00:17:30,710
He applied and?

230
00:17:30,710 --> 00:17:34,470
He wanted to go to the
beach and eat ice cream.

231
00:17:34,470 --> 00:17:36,190
That's right. It's this patient.

232
00:17:39,070 --> 00:17:41,080
It's so sad.

233
00:17:41,080 --> 00:17:44,950
You'd think a dying wish would
be something grandioso.

234
00:17:44,950 --> 00:17:46,640
But it's so simple.

235
00:17:49,140 --> 00:17:51,380
"I want to visit an art gallery."

236
00:17:51,380 --> 00:17:55,940
"I want to attend my favorite
soccer player's game."

237
00:17:55,940 --> 00:17:57,740
"I want to visit my hometown."

238
00:17:57,740 --> 00:18:00,610
Most of them are simple and ordinary.

239
00:18:00,610 --> 00:18:01,770
Yes.

240
00:18:01,770 --> 00:18:04,220
They must miss their healthy days.

241
00:18:06,360 --> 00:18:07,940
So I was thinking.

242
00:18:09,390 --> 00:18:11,030
We should do this, too.

243
00:18:11,030 --> 00:18:12,930
- Do what?
- For whom?

244
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:15,100
- For Yu Ri Hye.
- Huh?

245
00:18:15,120 --> 00:18:17,320
I was such a huge fan.

246
00:18:17,320 --> 00:18:19,360
I was happy because of her.

247
00:18:19,360 --> 00:18:21,040
Now she's ill...

248
00:18:21,040 --> 00:18:23,460
and doesn't have much time left.

249
00:18:23,460 --> 00:18:26,970
I'm a doctor now, and
there's nothing I can do.

250
00:18:26,970 --> 00:18:28,130
Man...

251
00:18:28,130 --> 00:18:29,870
I'm tearing up.

252
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:33,160
Do you guys really mean it?

253
00:18:34,040 --> 00:18:35,940
I don't see why not.

254
00:18:35,940 --> 00:18:38,460
You never know. Maybe we
can do something for her.

255
00:18:38,460 --> 00:18:39,860
- Really?
- Of course!

256
00:18:39,860 --> 00:18:41,250
- I'm in.
- I'm in, too.

257
00:18:41,250 --> 00:18:43,300
- I'm in!
- Right now?

258
00:18:43,300 --> 00:18:45,620
- One, two, three!
- We're in!

259
00:18:45,620 --> 00:18:47,460
Number one, egg mayo.

260
00:18:47,460 --> 00:18:50,540
And number eleven, BBQ chicken.

261
